I&#39;m using React.js and want to change the background color of the entire page. I can&#39;t figure out how to do this. Please help, thank you.
 Edit (Sep 2 &#39;18): I have a project on GitHub that I&#39;m linking  here. I don&#39;t have this project online right now, but in the  /client folder is the client server. Check it out. This is how I answered the question.
    The simplest solution is a bit hacky, but you can use raw javascript to modify the body style:
  A cleaner solution could be to use a head manager like  react-helmet or  next.js  Head component.
 import React from &#39;react&#39;;import {Helmet} from &#39;react-helmet&#39;;class Application extends React.Component { render () { return ( &lt;div className=&#34;application&#34;&gt; &lt;Helmet&gt; &lt;style&gt;{&#39;body { background-color: red; }&#39;}&lt;/style&gt; &lt;/Helmet&gt; ... &lt;/div&gt; ); }};
  In the end, there&#39;s a lot of tools providing cleaner ways to handle this. But if you don&#39;t want to rely on third party, the raw JS option might be good enough if you don&#39;t make it too interactive.
  Am I able to get document from within a reactjs component? I&#39;m trying to do this now but not having any luck.  document just comes back as undefined –  Ethan Davis
  @EthanDavis  document is a global variable in the browser; you can access it from anywhere. –  Simon Boudrias
  I&#39;m rendering my reactjs from a nodejs server.  document is undefined for me –  Ethan Davis
  @EthanDavis then the answer is going to be highly specific to how you architect your server side. But the same concept will stand true; you want to use raw JS to handle that as React doesn&#39;t render the  &lt;body&gt; tag. –  Simon Boudrias
  @DaveHowson the reason is manipulating the document manually requires you to handle cleanup/updates manually. As such it&#39;s not ideal because it&#39;s more error prone and requires more manual work. That being said, it is a valid use-case and React doesn&#39;t make it hard to do. So I&#39;d say it&#39;s okay to manipulate the document if you do not already use a framework/library that makes it easier. –  Simon Boudrias
      This is an extremely hard-coded solution very separate from other theming. Not good. –  doublejosh
          The above solutions tell about adding the external library to give the required functionality but instead what you can do is just go to your Index.css file and inside the already written &#39;body&#39; tag put &#34;background-color: &#39;color&#39;&#34; and its done
    Easiest solution of all !!! : useEffect(() =&gt; { document.body.style.backgroundColor = &#39;red&#39; }, []) –  Yannuth
